== Japanese content ==
{{神社
 | 名称=Tokari Shrine
 | 画像= [[File:Tokarishine.jpg|250px]]<br />Torii and worship hall
 | 所在地={{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|WD=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Habikino|Q694308|WD=Q694308|1=Habikino}} Shakudo<br/> (3-2053 Miya-chō, Tondabayashi, Osaka)
 | 位置= {{WikidataCoord|display=inline,title}}
 | 祭神={{ill|lt=Ukemochi|Q2280323|WD=Q2280323|1=Ukemochi}}<br/>{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Homudawake-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}<br/>{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|1=Ame-no-Koyane|WD=Q2564508}}
 | 社格={{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} (minor) / former {{ill|lt=Sonsha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}
 | 地図= {{Location map|Japan Osaka|label=Tokari Shrine|position=bottom|width=200|mark=Shinto torii icon vermillion.svg|marksize=15|float=center|caption=}}
{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=12|marker=religious-shinto|frame-align=center|frame-width=200|frame-height=200}}
}}
'''Tokari Shrine''' (とかりじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Shakudo, {{ill|lt=Habikino|Q694308|WD=Q694308|1=Habikino}}, {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|WD=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|lt=Sonsha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. In the Meiji period it was {{ill|lt=shrine merger|Q11590700|WD=Q11590700|lt=merged|1=Shrine Consolidation Policy}} into {{ill|lt=Migukurumitama Shrine|Q11608777|WD=Q11608777|1=Migukurumitama Shrine}} in Miya-chō, {{ill|lt=Tondabayashi|Q490928|WD=Q490928|1=Tondabayashi}}, becoming a {{ill|lt=sessha|Q135009904|WD=Q135009904|1=Sessha}} of that shrine, but a shrine of the same name was later rebuilt at the old site in Shakudo.

=== Enshrined deities ===
It enshrines {{ill|lt=Ukemochi|Q2280323|WD=Q2280323|1=Ukemochi}}, {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|lt=Homudawake-no-Mikoto|1=Emperor Ōjin}}, and {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Koyane|Q2564508|WD=Q2564508|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|1=Ame-no-Koyane}}.

''Dai Nihon Shi Jingi-shi'' and ''Chiri Shiryo'' state that it enshrines the ancestral deity of the Yora clan, descendants of {{ill|lt=Nigihayahi|Q10949054|WD=Q10949054|lt=Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto|1=Nigihayahi}}. ''Jinja Yōroku'' lists "deity unknown."

=== History ===
The shrine's founding history is unknown. It originally stood on Mount Tokari in the southwest of Shakudo village and was also called "Ō no Miya." In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} it is listed as a minor shrine. The shrine buildings were lost in warfare in the Tenshō era, and it was relocated in Keichō 17. In {{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}} (Meiji 5), it was ranked as a village shrine, but on October 12, Meiji 40, it was merged into Migukurumitama Shrine in Aza Miya, {{ill|lt=Kishi Village|Q18700084|WD=Q18700084|1=Kishi}} (present-day Miya-chō, Tondabayashi).

The time of rebuilding is unknown, but after the merger Tokari Shrine was rebuilt west of Saifuku-ji in Shakudo, Habikino.

